Does the proportion of books in the Goodreads database that lack text reviews differ significantly from 7%?

alpha = 0.05 H0: prop books lack text = 0.07 Ha: prop books lack text != 0.07

library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(infer)
books <- read_csv("data/books.csv") %>% clean_names()

Cleaning

books_tidy_2020 <- books %>% 
  filter(!is.na(average_rating)) %>% 
  rename(num_pages = number_num_pages)

Find proportion of books with no text reviews

observed_stat <- books_tidy_2020 %>% 
  group_by(text_reviews_count) %>% 
  summarise(prop = n()/nrow(books_tidy_2020)) %>% 
  filter(text_reviews_count == 0) %>% 
  pull(prop)

Task

Task - 15 mins Lets say you work for a publishing company and you want to use the Goodreads database to provide insight for future investment. Your CEO has decided they want to invest in French language books, if there is compelling evidence that there is a lack of such books in the market. Based on their experience of the industry, they have decided that if the proportion of books published in French is less than 1.5% then they will invest in publishing more. The hypothesis test corresponding to this business question is H0: French = 0.015 Ha: French < 0.015 Lets say answering this question is very important to the business because it will be used to justify investment, so we want to be stricter and perform a more conservative test. This is because, if we reject H0, we will be investing money, and so it will be more costly to make a type-I error (a false positive, i.e.we conclude that the proportion of books that are French is less than 1.5% even though it is not in reality), than a type-II error (a false negative). We would do this by decreasing our significance level for the test. By decreasing we reject H0 less often and need to have very strong evidence to do so. So, we will test this hypothesis at a significance level of =0.01.

Is the proportion of books written in French less than 1.5%

H0: prop_in_french = 0.015 Ha: prop_in_french < 0.015 alpha = 0.01

Get observed statistic

nrow(books_tidy_2020$language_code == "fre")

NULL

Get null distribution

null_dist_french_1.5 <- books_tidy_2020 %>% 
  mutate(in_french = if_else(language_code == "fre", "french", "not_french")) %>% 
  specify(response = in_french, success = "french") %>% 
  hypothesise(null = "point", p = 0.015) %>% 
  generate(reps = 5000, type = "simulate") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "prop")

Visualise null distribution and observed stat

distribution not very very normal

Calculate p value

If null hypothesis were true, that percentage of books written in French = 1.5%, then I would get this distribution if I were able to take 5000 samples of 10999 observations of all books. If this were true, I could still get a value of 0.0147 (as observed in my sample) or less 43% of the time. This means that the proportion of books written in French in this sample does not indicate that in reality, H0 is not true. Our sample proportion is very possible if the percent of books written in French is 1.5%.
